If you already know JavaScript, learning TypeScript is not like learning an entirely new programming language.
TypeScript is JavaScript with an additional type system.
You can continue using variables, functions, arrays, objects, classes, promises, async/await, modules, and almost everything else you already know. TypeScript simply adds tools that help you detect mistakes before your code reaches the browser or server.
This article covers the TypeScript fundamentals that matter most to someone coming from a JavaScript background.
What Is TypeScript?
TypeScript is a programming language built on top of JavaScript.
Every valid JavaScript program is generally also valid TypeScript. TypeScript adds static type checking and then compiles into regular JavaScript that browsers and Node.js can execute.
For example, this is valid JavaScript:
function add(a, b) {
return a + b;
}The same function in TypeScript can specify what kind of values it expects:
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
return a + b;
}
